        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>If you're in immediate danger, call 911.</strong> For a mental health crisis — thoughts of suicide, feeling like you can't cope, or just needing to talk to someone right now — use the resources below.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Crisis lines</h2>

        <h3>988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline</h3>
        <p><strong>Call or text: 988</strong></p>
        <p>Available 24/7, free, confidential. This is for any mental health crisis — not just suicide. If you're feeling overwhelmed, hopeless, or like you're at your limit, this line is for you. The people who answer are trained crisis counselors, not automated systems.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Call or text <strong>988</strong> from any phone in the U.S.</li>
          <li>Chat available at <a href="https://988lifeline.org/chat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">988lifeline.org/chat</a></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Crisis Text Line</h3>
        <p><strong>Text HOME to 741741</strong></p>
        <p>Text-based crisis support, available 24/7. Useful if you'd rather type than talk. A trained crisis counselor responds within minutes. Free and confidential.</p>

        <h2>Substance use and mental health</h2>

        <h3>SAMHSA National Helpline</h3>
        <p><strong>1-800-662-4357</strong></p>
        <p>The Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration helpline is free, confidential, and available 24/7 in English and Spanish. They can provide information, support, and referrals to local treatment facilities and support groups — for both substance use and mental health issues. No insurance required.</p>

        <h2>Parental stress</h2>

        <h3>Childhelp National Child Abuse Hotline</h3>
        <p><strong>1-800-422-4453</strong></p>
        <p>Available 24/7 with crisis intervention, information, and referrals. This line isn't just for abuse — it's also for parents who are feeling overwhelmed and are worried about their own reactions. Professional crisis counselors help parents find resources and de-escalate before situations become harmful. No judgment, just help.</p>

        <h3>Parents Anonymous</h3>
        <p>Runs peer-led support groups specifically for parents under stress — including single parents who are struggling. Free and available nationally. Find a group at <a href="https://parentsanonymous.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">parentsanonymous.org</a>.</p>

        <h2>Veterans</h2>
        <p>If you're a veteran, the <strong>Veterans Crisis Line</strong> is available specifically for you: call or text <strong>988 then press 1</strong>, or chat at <a href="https://www.veteranscrisisline.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">veteranscrisisline.net</a>. They have counselors with military experience.</p>

        <h2>Domestic violence (men can be victims too)</h2>
        <p>This one gets overlooked because the resources are often framed around women. But men experience domestic violence too, and it's underreported. If you are or have been in a situation involving abuse:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>National Domestic Violence Hotline:</strong> 1-800-799-7233 — call or text, 24/7, confidential. They work with all genders.</li>
          <li><strong>1in6</strong> (<a href="https://1in6.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1in6.org</a>) — support for men who have experienced sexual abuse or assault.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>If you're not in crisis — but need to talk</h2>
        <p>Not everything is a crisis. Sometimes you just need to vent or process something with someone outside your situation. A few options:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>7 Cups</strong> (<a href="https://www.7cups.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">7cups.com</a>) — free online chat with trained volunteer listeners. Not therapy, but a real person who will listen without judgment.</li>
          <li><strong>NAMI Helpline:</strong> 1-800-950-6264 — the National Alliance on Mental Illness helpline provides information, referrals, and support. Not a crisis line but very useful for navigating the mental health system.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>You're allowed to need help.</strong> Asking for it when you're at your limit isn't weakness — it's what you'd tell your kids to do. The line between "managing" and "not managing" can close fast when you're doing everything alone. Use these resources before you're in crisis if you can.</p>
        </div>

        <p>When you're ready for ongoing support rather than a crisis line, the <a href="{{ '/mental/counseling/' | url }}">Counseling guide</a> covers how to find a therapist and how to afford it, and the <a href="{{ '/mental/support-groups/' | url }}">Support Groups guide</a> covers peer communities built around exactly this situation.</p>
